IRST INDUSTRIAL REVOLUTION -- tNOTES ON CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen discussing wages, historians have traditionally concentrated on the level of wages, much less on how people were paid for their work. Important aspects were thus ignored such as how frequently were wages actually paid, how much of the wage was paid in non-monetary form - whether as traditional perquisites or community relief - especially when there was often insufficient coinage available to pay wages. Covering a wide geographical area, ranging from Spain to Finland, and time span, ranging from the sixteenth century to the 1930s, this volume offers fresh perspectives on key areas in social and economic history such as the relationship between customs, moral economy, wages and the market, changing pay and wage forms and the relationship between age, gender and wages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCompensation managementzEuropexHistory. 0aWage payment systemszEuropexHistory. 0aWageszEuropexHistory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh1 aDeceulaer, Harald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEeckhout, Patricia Van den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGooren, Henny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGálvez-Muñoz, Lina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeger, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeikkinen, Sakari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuberman, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumphries, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 